<br>
After one load of banded boot molds, it became obvious that this was NOT a viable path.  2 skillups but only about a 40% success rate; the PP:skillup ratio was pretty skewed.  Note that this took me from 102 to 104; the trivial on banded boots is 135, a pretty big gap.<br>
<br>
So, back to metal bits for a while.  1 backpack full of bits sufficied to make skewers to 114 (trivial is 115, but I hit 114 at the very end of a load of molds) and pots to 121 (again, one shy of the trivial, but had just finished a full load of molds).  <br>
<br>
I then shifted over to banded boots again.  I still had almost an entire pack full of metal bits, but running back and forth to North Ro for needle and thimble molds looked to impose a huge time sink in the process, aggravated by the need for 2 molds for each sewing kit.<br>
<br>
Banded boots went pretty quickly; the very first run yielded 5 skill ups in short order.  The pace slowed down quite a bit, but the success rate remained good and I was able to reach the trivial point (135) with only a modest expenditure of PP.  I then shifted to banded mantles.  Both these and gauntlets are two-sheet items that trival at 168, but the molds for mantles are cheaper.  About 50 combines later I had reached 139 skill, at which point I called it a night.<br>
<br>
It looks like Weilaynd will need another small cash infusion from his older brother Amerygn in order to reach 175, the end of the road for banded (banded cloaks are the most difficult piece and are trivial at 175).  At that point most smiths have to shift to fine plate for skill, but if I can scrounge up enough HQ ore Weilaynd, being a human smith, has a cultural option - sea farer's bucklers trivial at 188, and while they need an HQ sheet of metal don't require any other specialized components (paddings, tempers, etc.).  At that point, I hope to be ready to hunt up some sea tempers, more HQ ore and give some imbued field plate pieces a try.<br>
<br>
More details to follow!<br>
<br>
